I   wrote in August about Elon Musk=E2=80=99s efforts to get out of buying =
Twitter Inc.:

The situation is that the richest person in the world, Elon Musk, has $44 b=
illion riding on the question of whether Twitter Inc. is doing a massive lo=
ng-running fraud on its users, its advertisers and its shareholders. Musk h=
as claimed that it is, with no evidence at all, just a vague feeling that h=
e has. If he=E2=80=99s right and there is a massive fraud, then he can get =
out of his agreement to buy Twitter for about $44 billion. If he=E2=80=99s =
wrong, he has to buy Twitter.=C2=A0
This situation is extremely well known. There are incentives. If you have s=
omething to do with Twitter, or you know something about Twitter, or you ar=
e in the business of counting Twitter bots, then you should take a few minu=
tes and ask yourself: Well, do I know anything about Twitter doing any mass=
ive frauds? If you do =E2=80=A6 look, I don=E2=80=99t know exactly what you=
 can do with that. I am not at all sure that you can actually go to Elon Mu=
sk and be like =E2=80=9Chey I=E2=80=99ve got a pile of fraud documents, the=
y=E2=80=99re yours for $1 billion.=E2=80=9D (He could send you a subpoena a=
nd get them for free?) Even if you did strike a deal with him, he=E2=80=99s=
 notoriously bad about sticking to his deals. Still. I just have a vague ge=
neral sense that saving the richest person in the world $44 billion is a go=
od career move.=C2=A0
So you should expect that, over the next month or two, as Musk=E2=80=99s tr=
ial date with Twitter approaches, people will be popping up to say =E2=80=
=9Coh sure Twitter is a fraud, massive fraud, totally, I have proof, Elon, =
call me.=E2=80=9D

Well, that case goes to trial this month, and  here=E2=80=99s this:

Another Twitter whistleblower is considering taking the stand when Elon Mus=
k faces the company in court over his $44 billion buyout deal later in two =
weeks =E2=80=94 and he may have a few things to say about bots, The Post ha=
s learned. ...
The would-be whistleblower, a former Twitter employee, claims to have been =
involved in an internal report several years ago that supposedly concluded =
that at least 30% of Twitter=E2=80=99s daily active users are automated spa=
m accounts.
=E2=80=9CTwitter execs laughed when they were told about the report and sai=
d, =E2=80=98We have always had a bot problem,=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D the potenti=
al whistleblower said in an interview with The Post. =E2=80=A6
The potential whistleblower said that Twitter=E2=80=99s chosen metric to me=
asure bots =E2=80=94 called Monetizable Daily Active Users, or mDAUs =E2=80=
=94 is overly narrow and fails to fully capture the extent of the site=E2=
=80=99s spam problem. He said Twitter may not be lying when it says that le=
ss than 5% of its mDAUs are bots, but takes issue with using mDAU as a meas=
urement in the first place and claims the company has not been transparent =
with investors.=C2=A0

Yes look if he testifies that Twitter=E2=80=99s securities filings were acc=
urate, but he didn=E2=80=99t like=C2=A0them, then that won=E2=80=99t help M=
usk very much will it. The problem here is that the incentives are so large=
 and well-known that they will attract a lot of people who are eager to hel=
p but have nothing to offer.

