10px;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Programming note:</strong><em> Money S=
tuff will be off tomorrow, back on Thursday.</em></p>
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Barclays!</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In March 2022, Barclays Plc<a class=3D"footnot=
e-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: non=
e !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; borde=
r-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; =
display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>=C2=A0discovered an oopsie involving a fairly technical detail of US se=
curities law. When a=C2=A0company sells securities to the public, in the US=
, it has to register those securities, filing a registration statement with=
 the US Securities and Exchange Commission that says what kinds and amounts=
 of securities it plans to sell. This is very important. If you sell securi=
ties=C2=A0without<em>=C2=A0</em>properly registering them, you can get in t=
rouble. One kind of trouble that you can get in is that the SEC can sue you=
. Another kind of trouble that you can get in is that the people who=C2=A0b=
uy<em>=C2=A0</em>the securities can demand their money back. If you sell pe=
ople stock for $20 per share, and then a year later they notice that you di=
d not properly register the offering, and the stock is now at $5, you have =
to give them their $20 back. (If the stock is at $30, they can keep it; the=
y don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0<em>have=C2=A0</em>to take their money back.)=C2=A0Thi=
s creates a lot of bad risk for you, which you can avoid by filing the righ=
t forms.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">When the company is a startup selling stock=C2=
=A0to the public for the first time, the=C2=A0registration process is calle=
d an =E2=80=9Cinitial public offering=E2=80=9D and is a big deal. When the =
company is a giant bank that sells dozens of securities every day, it is no=
t. It files a =E2=80=9Cshelf registration statement,=E2=80=9D letting it se=
ll a large=C2=A0amount of a wide range of securities over time, and then ea=
ch day it sells some more securities =E2=80=9Coff that shelf,=E2=80=9D and =
when it has sold all of the securities covered by the shelf registration st=
atement then it files a new one and starts over again. And it is all pretty=
 administrative and boring.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The bank uses the shelf to sell a range of sec=
urities: bonds and notes to fund its general activities, structured notes (=
basically customized derivatives wrapped in bonds of the bank and sold to r=
ich people), and (at Barclays) <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusine=
ss.com/click/29264112.275527/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZXRmc3RyZWFtLmNvbS9uZXdzL2Jhcm=
NsYXlzLXN1c3BlbmRzLWV0bi1yYW5nZS1hZnRlci1wYXBlcndvcmstaXNzdWUv/607f07ceef4b=
8524a319a23cBd5f3530a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targe=
t=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bor=
der-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: s=
olid; background-color: #ccc;"> exchange-traded products</a> that give cust=
omers exposure to things like oil prices or the VIX volatility index. Every=
 day the bank needs funding, and customers want to do trades, and some of t=
hose trades come in the form of securities issued off the shelf.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Normally the SEC makes this process very easy =
for big well-known companies. A =E2=80=9Cwell-known seasoned issuer,=E2=80=
=9D or WKSI, under US securities law can file shelf registration statements=
 that don=E2=80=99t even specify a maximum amount of securities, and they a=
re automatically =E2=80=9Ceffective=E2=80=9D: The company can just sell sec=
urities immediately, as soon as it files the registration statement, withou=
t any SEC review. The WKSI standards are in <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bl=
oombergbusiness.com/click/29264112.275527/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubGF3LmNvcm5lbGwuZ=
WR1L2Nmci90ZXh0LzE3LzIzMC40MDU/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe9e35eaf" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
SEC Rule 405</a> and Instruction I.A on=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.b=
loombergbusiness.com/click/29264112.275527/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9maWxl=
cy9mb3Jtcy0zLnBkZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB68d26ea1" itemprop=3D"StoryLink=
" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-d=
ecoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: =
#000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Form S-3</a>,=
 and the basic requirements are that you have been public for at least a ye=
ar, you have a stock market capitalization of at least $700 million, and yo=
ur annual and quarterly SEC reports are up-to-date. The intuition is that i=
f you are a big company that has been public for a while, you can just say =
=E2=80=9Chey we=E2=80=99re selling some securities,=E2=80=9D and then you d=
o it, without a lot of formalities.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Barclays is a big company that has been public=
 for a while, so it was a WKSI, and it used its WKSI status to sell lots of=
 structured notes and exchange-traded products every day.=C2=A0But there is=
 one more requirement for being a WKSI, which is that you can=E2=80=99t hav=
e committed any securities fraud in the last three years.<a class=3D"footno=
te-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: no=
ne !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bord=
er-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important;=
 display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>=C2=A0It is a=C2=A0fact of life=C2=A0that big=C2=A0banks are constantly=
 getting in trouble for some form or other of securities fraud. At every on=
e of the large legacy investment banks, somebody in some division is commit=
ting securities fraud=C2=A0<em>right now</em>. But the WKSI rules really ar=
e intended to let big public companies issue securities with a minimum of f=
uss, and nobody needs that more than a bank selling new notes every day. An=
d in general the banks are not getting in trouble for fraudulently issuing =
structured notes off their WKSI shelf registration statements. (<a href=3D"=
https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29264112.275527/aHR0cHM6Ly93d=
3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZXdzL3ByZXNzLXJlbGVhc2UvMjAxNi0xMjk/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23c=
Bd851c642" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank"=
 style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-w=
idth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgr=
ound-color: #ccc;">Sometimes</a>, though!) If someone on some mortgage-bond=
 trading desk does some light fraud, it is odd to punish the exchange-trade=
d-notes people by making it more inconvenient for them to register securiti=
es.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For a long time, the SEC dealt with this by gr=
anting =E2=80=9CWKSI=C2=A0waivers=E2=80=9D to banks pretty liberally: Each =
time a bank got caught doing something bad, it would confess its=C2=A0sins =
and pay a big fine, and then the SEC would say =E2=80=9Cokay but you still =
get to be a WKSI.=E2=80=9D And the banks could keep issuing securities effi=
ciently.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">At some point this became controversial, for r=
easons that <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/292641=
12.275527/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTUtM=
DItMDUvc2VjLWRvZXNuLXQtdGFrZS1pdHMtYXV0b21hdGljLXB1bmlzaG1lbnRzLXRvby1saXRl=
cmFsbHk_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTAwNDIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc29=
1cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIxMDA0JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/6=
07f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB2be38034" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"items=
cope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !imp=
ortant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bott=
om-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> I have never understood</a>, and=
=C2=A0people objected that the SEC was giving out too many of these waivers=
. So in 2015 the SEC collected some fines and=C2=A0gave out some waivers fo=
r foreign-exchange manipulation, and <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomberg=
business.com/click/29264112.275527/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZXdzL3N0YXRl=
bWVudC9zdGVpbi13YWl2ZXJzLWdyYW50ZWQtZGlzc2VudGluZy1zdGF0ZW1lbnQ/607f07ceef4=
b8524a319a23cB83e6baf4" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targ=
et=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bo=
rder-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: =
solid; background-color: #ccc;">SEC Commissioner Kara Stein dissented</a>, =
noting that the SEC was granting =E2=80=9CBarclays its third WKSI waiver si=
nce 2007.=E2=80=9D (UBS AG was on its seventh waiver and JPMorgan Chase &am=
p; Co. its sixth.) The next year Barclays got its <a href=3D"https://link.m=
ail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29264112.275527/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9=
ydWxlcy9vdGhlci8yMDE2LzMzLTEwMDEyLnBkZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBcf0efe86" =
itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"c=
olor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; =
border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color:=
 #ccc;"> fourth WKSI waiver</a>, for a <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombe=
rgbusiness.com/click/29264112.275527/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZXdzL3ByZX=
NzLXJlbGVhc2UvMjAyMi0xNzk/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB77dee5ff" itemprop=3D"St=
oryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000;=
 text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-=
color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> $361 =
million settlement</a> over some bad dark-pool stuff.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In May 2017 Barclays signed a fairly run-of-th=
e-mill <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29264112.27=
5527/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZXdzL3ByZXNzLXJlbGVhc2UvMjAxNy05OA/607f07c=
eef4b8524a319a23cB676f963e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" =
target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important=
; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-sty=
le: solid; background-color: #ccc;">settlement with the SEC</a> in which it=
 agreed to pay $97 million for overcharging some clients for mutual funds. =
Securities fraud, sure, why not.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footno=
te-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bot=
tom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !im=
portant; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>=C2=A0This one, though, was finally a bridge too far, and it did not ge=
t a WKSI waiver. I don=E2=80=99t know why this one was the one.=C2=A0But af=
ter that Barclays stopped being a WKSI.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"=
#footnote-4" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bor=
der-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: n=
one !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-b=
lock;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This meant that instead of occasionally filing=
 shelf registration statements saying =E2=80=9Chey we=E2=80=99re gonna sell=
 some securities, look out,=E2=80=9D Barclays had to occasionally file shel=
f registration statements saying =E2=80=9Chey we=E2=80=99re gonna sell $___=
____ of securities, look out.=E2=80=9D And in the summer of=C2=A02019, Barc=
lays filed a shelf registration statement saying that it would sell up to <=
a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29264112.275527/aHR=
0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzMxMjA3MC8wMDAxMTkzMTI1MT=
kyMDY5MjUvZDc3ODQ5M2RmM2EuaHRt/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB8f16bf54" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
