<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In March, when Barclays discovered this oopsie=
, it notified the market and estimated that it would <a href=3D"https://lin=
k.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29264112.275527/aHR0cHM6Ly9ob21lLmJhcmNs=
YXlzL2NvbnRlbnQvZGFtL2hvbWUtYmFyY2xheXMvZG9jdW1lbnRzL2ludmVzdG9yLXJlbGF0aW9=
ucy9JUk5ld3NQcmVzZW50YXRpb25zLzIwMjJOZXdzLzIwMjIwMzI4LUltcGFjdC1vZiUyMG92ZX=
ItaXNzdWFuY2UtdW5kZXItQkJQTEMtVVMtU2hlbGYucGRm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf22=
50227" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" sty=
le=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width=
: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background=
-color: #ccc;">cost about=C2=A0=C2=A3450 million</a> in rescission, but tha=
t number has grown over time. The intuition is roughly: If you bought a str=
uctured note or exchange-traded product=C2=A0from Barclays in late 2021 or =
early 2022, you were making some sort of bet in which Barclays would give y=
ou more than your money back=C2=A0if something happened (often: if the mark=
et was up) but Barclays would give you less than your money back if somethi=
ng else happened (often: if the market was down). If Barclays gave you more=
 than your money back, you=E2=80=99re happy, and you did not take the resci=
ssion offer. If Barclays gave you less than your money back, you were sad, =
and you did take the rescission offer. Between March and now, markets went =
down a lot, so more people are sad and want rescission.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">When this came out in March, <a href=3D"https:=
//link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29264112.275527/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmx=
vb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDMtMjgvYmFyY2xheXMtc29sZC10b2=
8tbWFueS1ub3Rlcz9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMDA0MjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJ=
nV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjEwMDQmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5=
c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB27e6a151" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> we talked about it here=
</a>. I want to go back to two things I said at the time. First, my assumpt=
ions about how this happened:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If some junior person in the internal legal te=
am leaves, and forgets to pass along the =E2=80=9Cshelfcapacityleft_07.xls=
=E2=80=9D spreadsheet to her successor, and it stops being updated =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0then, uh. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0=C2=A0You just keep bopping along as thou=
gh everything was fine, and then one day a new junior analyst starts on the=
 legal team and finds the =E2=80=9Cshelfcapacityleft_07.xls=E2=80=9D spread=
sheet in a folder and asks the vice president =E2=80=9Chey what is this,=E2=
=80=9D and the VP looks, and she realizes what it is, and they check the ma=
th 20 times because it seems too horrible to be true, and then they all lea=
ve for the bar at noon because it is not a fixable error and they will miss=
 each other when they=E2=80=99re all fired tomorrow. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I hope that they will eventually publish the f=
ull report and we can find out what the actual file name of =E2=80=9Cshelfc=
apacityleft_07.xls=E2=80=9D was and when it was last updated. Perhaps we wi=
ll learn the name of the junior analyst in the legal department responsible=
 for updating the spreadsheet, and which law school she left for when she s=
topped updating it.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I feel like I captured=C2=A0the general <em>fe=
el</em> of it, but it did not occur to me that there=C2=A0<em>was never a s=
preadsheet at all</em>. It=E2=80=99s not that they stopped updating it, it=
=E2=80=99s that it never existed. Not great!</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Second, my assumptions about how the SEC would=
 react:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It is not a fixable error because =
the rules are harsh, and there is no no-harm-no-foul rule for illegal secur=
ities offerings. If you sell securities without a valid registration statem=
ent =E2=80=94=C2=A0as Barclays did =E2=80=94=C2=A0then you have to offer to=
 buy the securities back at the price you sold them for. If the securities =
were structured notes and ETNs =E2=80=94=C2=A0that is, bets that some index=
 will go up or down, or weird exotic options bets =E2=80=94=C2=A0and if you=
 don=E2=80=99t catch the mistake for a whole year, then some of them will h=
ave gone down a lot. You sold them for $100 and now they are worth $50 and =
you have to buy them back at $100. (Others will have gone=C2=A0<em>up=C2=A0=
</em>a lot, but you don=E2=80=99t get to buy=C2=A0<em>those</em>=C2=A0back =
at par: You have to offer to rescind all of your sales, but the holders can=
 decline.) You can call up the SEC and say =E2=80=9Cwe messed up a little b=
it but no one was harmed, sorry,=E2=80=9D and the SEC will say =E2=80=9Cah =
yes we see, we understand, no one was harmed and you didn=E2=80=99t mean it=
,=E2=80=9D and they will feel sorry for you, but they will still make you o=
ffer to buy back all the ETNs. And then you=E2=80=99ll lose 450 million pou=
nds.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Well. I mean. That=E2=80=99s what=C2=A0<em>I=
=C2=A0</em>would say, if I were the SEC! I would say =E2=80=9Clook yes ther=
e=E2=80=99s no way around it, this is going to cost you hundreds of million=
s of dollars to buy back all those structured notes and exchange-traded pro=
ducts that you sold. I=E2=80=99m sorry, it=E2=80=99s very unfair: The specu=
lators who bought those notes made a bet, and they lost, and they get their=
 money back due to a random administrative windfall. You didn=E2=80=99t act=
ually deceive or defraud them in any way, and your dumb administrative mist=
ake didn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0<em>harm=C2=A0</em>them, but they do get to take ad=
vantage of it to get their money back, sorry.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The actual SEC=C2=A0<em>fined Barclays $200 mi=
llion on top of the rescission costs</em>, and <a href=3D"https://link.mail=
.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29264112.275527/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZX=
dzL3ByZXNzLXJlbGVhc2UvMjAyMi0xNzk/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cD77dee5ff" itempr=
op=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: =
#000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border=
-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;=
"> said this</a>:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">"This case highlights why it is es=
sential for firms like Barclays to have robust internal controls over their=
 offers and sales of securities," said Gurbir S. Grewal, Director of the SE=
C=E2=80=99s Division of Enforcement. "While we acknowledge Barclays=E2=80=
=99 efforts to identify, disclose and remediate this conduct, the control d=
eficiencies and the scope of the conduct at issue here was simply staggerin=
g. The time for other firms employing similar shelf registrations to take n=
otice and improve their internal compliance and control functions is now."<=
/p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Just unbelievably harsh! Sure yes this was ver=
y <em>bad</em>, but the only=C2=A0<em>victim=C2=A0</em>of it was Barclays; =
the investors who bought unregistered securities were not deceived in any w=
ay, and many of them ended up with a random windfall. Sure yes Barclays=E2=
=80=99s=C2=A0<em>shareholders=C2=A0</em>suffered by having to pay out that =
random windfall, but it=E2=80=99s not like fining them $200 million more ma=
kes that any better.=C2=A0</p>
